# Architecture plan for mobile layout issues #115-#117

## Project/module structure
- `frontend/src/App.tsx` owns the React route/component structure for the TLHN landing and network pages. The three issues are presentation/layout-only and should not change backend APIs or shared DTO contracts.
- `frontend/src/styles.css` is the primary implementation surface. It contains the Tailwind component-layer classes for the global shell, landing hero/story, countdown, tally cards, network sections, and chat feed ordering.
- `shared/src/*` remains the source of product/faction constants and types; no schema/type additions are needed for these issues.
- `backend/src/*` and database migrations are out of scope unless validation reveals an unrelated build break; these issues do not require persistence changes.

## Issue dependencies and sequencing
1. #115 should be implemented first because global shell/header padding and nav sizing affect every page and establish the mobile spacing baseline.
2. #116 should follow because the landing logo/story must be tuned inside the global shell spacing from #115.
3. #117 should be last because the network page spacing, countdown/tally compaction, and mobile feed ordering depend on the same responsive spacing rules and may need final balancing against header/shell changes.

## Key design decisions
- Keep TLHN branding and copy exactly as defined in `PRODUCT.md` and shared constants; only responsive sizing/spacing changes are planned.
- Use mobile-first Tailwind utilities in `frontend/src/styles.css`, restoring current desktop/tablet appearance with `sm:`/larger responsive overrides where requested.
- Prefer CSS ordering/flex/grid utilities for the mobile network reorder so `App.tsx` semantics and API behavior remain stable.
- Preserve accessibility and existing scroll/history behavior for the unified feed; moving the feed visually on mobile must not remove labels, polling, or infinite-history loading.
- Validate with the existing workspace build/lint scripts after each implementation session, focusing screenshots/manual checks on phone-width layouts and ensuring desktop remains unchanged at `sm:`+ breakpoints.
